 {"id": "franken_networkx-astertype", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] find_asteroidal_triple returned tuple; nx returns list", "description": "fnx.find_asteroidal_triple forwarded the Rust binding's tuple result unchanged; nx.find_asteroidal_triple returns a list [u,v,w]. Consumers doing isinstance(r, list) or equality-comparing against nx's contract would fail. Fixed wrapper to coerce the Rust result to list (preserving None for 'no AT'). Verified on cycle_graph(6): nx=[0,2,4], fnx now=[0,2,4].", "status": "closed", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Coerce Rust tuple result to list", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-asplint", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] average_shortest_path_length returned 0.0 (float) on n=1; nx returns 0 (int)", "description": "nx.average_shortest_path_length returns literal int 0 for the single-node graph (early-return before any division); fnx's Rust-native path returned 0.0 float. isinstance(..., int) checks downstream would diverge. Fixed Python wrapper to short-circuit n==1 with return 0 (int). Verified for Graph/DiGraph/MultiGraph single-node inputs. Multi-node inputs unchanged (still return float).", "status": "closed", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Early int-return for n==1", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-effdir", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] global_efficiency / local_efficiency accepted DiGraphs silently; nx rejects with NetworkXNotImplemented", "description": "nx.global_efficiency and nx.local_efficiency are @not_implemented_for('directed') and raise NetworkXNotImplemented on DiGraph input. fnx's Rust-native bindings silently computed and returned a float. Users expecting the standard contract (and frameworks that use it as a capability signal) would get wrong behavior. Fixed Python wrappers to raise NetworkXNotImplemented('not implemented for directed type') when G.is_directed(). Also fixed global_efficiency to return literal int 0 for n<2 matching nx's denom==0 branch (g_eff stays int). MultiGraph path unchanged (correct). efficiency(G,u,v) already rejected DiGraphs.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Gate on G.is_directed() and int-return for n<2", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-binomlabels", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] binomial_tree produced different node labels than nx", "description": "fnx.binomial_tree for n>=2 emitted a tree structurally isomorphic to nx's but with different labels (edges like (1,3) where nx yields (2,3)). nx's algorithm is a clone-and-shift scheme producing a specific canonical labelling; downstream code that compares edge lists directly broke. Fix: always use the Python clone-and-shift path (mirrors nx exactly); drop the Rust fast path for default create_using.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python clone-and-shift labels match nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-tadm2", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] tadpole_graph(m=2,...) raised NetworkXError; nx accepts the degenerate case", "description": "nx.tadpole_graph accepts m=2 (cycle-part is a single edge) and attaches the tail. The Rust binding required m>=3 and raised NetworkXError. Route m<3 cases through the Python fallback that calls cycle_graph(m_nodes) so the m=2 degenerate output plus any tail matches nx exactly.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Gate Rust path on m>=3", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-circself", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] circulant_graph rejected n=0 and silently dropped self-loops", "description": "nx.circulant_graph accepts n=0 (empty) and produces self-loops when an offset is divisible by n (e.g. n=1 with offset 1; n=2 with offset 2). The Rust binding rejected n=0 entirely and the fast path dropped self-loops, breaking parity. Fix: only delegate to Rust when n>=2 AND no offset is divisible by n; fall back to the Python path (which already emits correct self-loops) otherwise.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Gate Rust path on self-loop-free case", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-windvalid", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] windmill_graph silently accepted n<2 producing a malformed graph", "description": "nx.windmill_graph raises NetworkXError('A windmill graph must have at least two cliques') for n<2 and NetworkXError('The cliques must have at least two nodes') for k<2. fnx's wrapper delegated straight to Rust: windmill_graph(0, 3) returned a 1-node Graph and windmill_graph(1, 3) returned a 3-node triangle, neither of which is a windmill graph. Validate n<2 and k<2 with nx's exact wording so callers can't silently construct wrong graphs.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side validation with nx messages", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-knesvalid", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] kneser_graph accepted n<=0 / k<=0 / k>n; nx rejects", "description": "nx.kneser_graph requires n>0 and 0<k<=n; rejects otherwise with NetworkXError. fnx accepted n=0 and k=0, producing a 1-node graph whose single node was the empty tuple (). Added the nx-compatible validation so invalid inputs raise the same message. Keeps k==n accepted (returns 1-node, 0-edge graph) as nx does.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side validation with nx messages", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
